{[%evp 0,25,18,20,24,24,29,29,35,15,11,17,27,39,47,49,58,54,46,34,49,61,52,56,60,51,65,68]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Bg4 $6 {The idea behind this move is to exchange on f3 and challenge the center with Nfd7-e5. With this interesting plan, Black compensates by giving up the light-squared bishop, which is Black's most important piece. Without it, Black's attacking chances are significantly reduced.} 7. h3 $1 {A very important move. We immediately question Black's idea behind 6...Bg4 and prevent 7...Qc8 with the follow-up Bh3.} (7. O-O Qc8 8. Bf4 $14) 7... Bxf3 (7... Bf5 $6 {doesn't make sense, as it allows us to gain multiple tempos and develop quickly with initiative.} 8. g4 $1 Be6 9. d5 Bd7 10. O-O $16) 8. Bxf3 Nc6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7e5]} 9. Rb1 $5 $146 {With this move, we slightly postpone castling. If Black proceeds with the standard plan ...Nd7-e5, our idea of h4-h5 becomes more effective with the rook on h1. The rook on h1 also prevents Black's typical plan of ...Kh8, ...Ng8, and ...Bh6, as we can immediately push h5, leaving Black no time to implement their idea.} ({With} 9. O-O {we transpose into the main line, where I'll demonstrate White's typical plans. This should help illustrate the advantages of delaying castling.} Nd7 10. e3 e5 11. d5 Ne7 12. e4 Kh8 $1 {[%cal Ge7g8,Gg7h6]} (12... f5 {Black's most common continuations allow us the chance to play} 13. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5]} Nf6 14. Bg5 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h6 (14... Qd7 15. Kg2 $1) 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. h5 $1 {The triumph of White's ideas, which began with 13.h4, is complete. Of course, we want to open Black's kingside, but our plan focuses on exploiting and dominating the light squares.}) 13. Kg2 Ng8 14. h4 $1 {We stick to our plan anyway! While Black aims to exchange the dark-squared bishops, we will continue working to open the h-file. If Black closes it with ...g5 at some point, it would be ideal for us, as in the KID, Black typically plays on the kingside, which would then remain closed, allowing us to focus entirely on the queenside.} Bh6 15. h5 a5 (15... Bxc1 16. Rxc1 a5 17. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4]} Nh6 18. Rh1 g5 19. g4 $14 {[%cal Gh1e1,Ge1e3,Gb2b4] This position is perfect for us, as the closed kingside ensures Black has no active counterplay there, letting us concentrate entirely on our queenside plans.}) (15... Kg7 16. Rh1 $14 f5 $2 (16... a5 17. Bxh6+ Nxh6 18. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Gh1h2,Ga1h1,Yg6g5,Yg3g4]}) 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. exf5 gxf5 19. Rh5 $18 {1-0 Omelja,A (2499)-Kamsky,G (2665) Titled Tuesday intern op 16th Feb Chess.com INT blitz 2021 (7)}) 16. Rh1 Bxc1 17. Rxc1 (17. Qxc1 Nc5 18. Qe3 Kg7 19. b3 $14 {[%cal Ga1b1,Ga2a3]}) 17... Nc5 18. Qc2 Kg7 19. Rh2 $14 {[%cal Gc1h1] Here, we will either open the h-file, or if Black closes the kingside with ...g5, we can swiftly regroup our pieces on the queenside.}) 9... e6 $5 {As we've seen, playing ...e5 proves very dangerous for Black, so now he is trying to maintain the tension and patiently wait for White's idea. Nevertheless, we stick to our plan with} ({If Black continues with his typical plan starting with} 9... Nd7 {after} 10. e3 e5 (10... a5 11. h4 $1 h5 12. Bg2 (12. g4 $5 hxg4 13. Bxg4 f5 14. Be2 Kh7 15. Kd2 $1 $14 {[%cal Gd2c2,Gd1g1] Beautiful move. We will bring the king to safety on the queenside, while simultaneously positioning our queen for a much faster attack along the g-file.}) 12... Nf6 13. O-O Qd7 14. b3 $16 {[%cal Gc1b2] This position, without Black's light-squared bishops, is strategically untenable.}) 11. d5 Ne7 12. e4 f5 13. h4 {We can clearly see the idea behind postponing castling, as now the maneuver Kh8-Ng8-Bh6 is no longer possible.} Nf6 (13... Kh8 {Delaying castling proves to be a powerful idea here. With the rook still on h1} 14. h5 $18 {becomes a deadly blow for Black, creating immediate threats and leaving him in a precarious position.}) 14. h5 Qd7 15. Bg5 $16) 10. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h6 11. Kf1 a6 12. Kg2 ({A solid alternative could be} 12. Be3 Rb8 13. Qd2 h5 14. Kg2 $14) 12... Qd7 13. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gh1d1,Yd4d5,Yb2b4] Generally, I don't believe the whole idea behind 6...Bg4 is strategically justified. As we saw, 9...0-0 is perfectly fine for White, but I think we can achieve much more with 9.Rb1!? This keeps the rook on h1, making the h4-h5 idea even more effective.} *

