1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 c5 {Currently, one of the best choices against the Fianchetto System. It gained significant popularity after Gawain Jones' Chessable course in 2021.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Na5 9. Nd2 e6 {We'll keep Jones' recommendation as our primary line here.} (9... a6 {Black's most common continuation.} 10. Rb1 $1 ({Here} 10. Qc2 {is the most played move by White. I don't like it because after} b5 $1 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qb6 13. Nc3 Bf5 14. e4 Bc8 15. Rb1 Ba6 16. Rd1 Ng4 $132 {Black reaches a very active position.}) 10... Rb8 11. b3 b5 12. Qc2 e5 (12... e6 13. Bb2 exd5 14. cxd5 Re8 15. e4 Bd7 16. Nd1 $1 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gh2h3,Gf1e1,Gd1e3] A typical maneuver we've already seen a few times in this theoretical line. The knight on e3 will be very useful, especially in combination with h3 and f4. I don't see any counterplay for Black.}) (12... bxc4 $6 {This move usually brings an advantage only to White.} 13. bxc4 Rxb1 {Here, we have two good options; whichever you choose, White will have a much better position.} 14. Qxb1 (14. Ncxb1 Bd7 15. Bb2 Qc7 16. Bc3 Rb8 {Wang,Y (2711)-Jianu,V (2588) Bazna 2014} 17. f4 $16) 14... Bd7 15. Nd1 $14 {[%cal Gb1c2,Gc1b2,Gb2c3] /}) 13. e4 Bh6 (13... Bd7 14. Nd1 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd1e3,Gc1b2]}) 14. Re1 $1 $146 Ne8 15. Bf1 Bd7 16. Nd1 f5 17. exf5 Bxf5 (17... gxf5 $6 18. Ne3 Ng7 19. Bd3 Bg5 20. Ng2 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg1h1]} e4 21. Be2 $16 {[%cal Gf2f3]}) 18. Ne4 Bxc1 19. Rxc1 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gf1d3,Gd1e3] We have a nice KID structure. Bd3 and Ne3 are coming, while the knight on a5 is misplaced, and Black will need a lot of time to bring it back into the game.}) 10. Rb1 $5 exd5 11. cxd5 Bd7 12. b3 b5 13. Qc2 b4 (13... Re8 14. Bb2 b4 $6 15. Nce4 Nxe4 (15... Bf5 $6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. e4 Bd7 18. f4 $16 {1-0 Kourek,J (2258)-Handl,M (2072) CZE-chT2d 0607 Czech Republic 2006 (3)}) 16. Bxe4 $1 Bb5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Bd3 a6 19. Rbc1 Qf6 20. e3 Nb7 21. Rfe1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge3e4,Gg1g2,Gf2f4] White will gradually improve the position with Kg2, followed by e4 and f4. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.55.}) 14. Nd1 Re8 15. Ne3 h5 {The novelty recommended by Jones. Black threat to open the h-file with ...h4 and possibly launch an attack along it, so this move requires careful precision. Additionally, maintaining control over the g4 square is valuable, adding to the importance of accurate play here.} (15... Bh6 16. Bb2 $1 Qe7 17. Kh1 $1 Bxe3 18. fxe3 Ng4 19. e4 Ne5 (19... Ne3 $2 {looks tempting, but in reality, it's a big mistake. Black's position becomes so weak on the dark squares that it is completely lost for him.} 20. Qd3 Nxf1 21. Rxf1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Rd3a6]} a6 22. g4 $18 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gd3h3,Gb2f6]}) 20. Rbc1 f6 21. a3 bxa3 22. Bxa3 Nb7 {½-½ Duchardt,A (2425)-Szerlak,A (2386) EU-ch 2022 sf10 email ICCF email} 23. Nc4 $1 Rf8 24. Ra1 Nd8 {[%cal Gd8f7]} 25. Bb2 Ndf7 26. h3 Bb5 27. Ne3 Kg7 28. Bc3 $14) 16. Bb2 Bb5 ({My student, a strong FM, played} 16... h4 {against me. It was a completely logical move. Black aims to open the h-file and possibly bring his knight to g5 via h7.} 17. Bf3 $1 Bh3 (17... Nh7 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. a3 Ng5 20. Qb2+ Qf6 (20... Kg8 $6 21. axb4 cxb4 22. Qd4 $16 {[%csl Rb4]}) 21. Qxf6+ Kxf6 22. Ra1 $14 {[%cal Gf3g2,Yg5f3,Ye2f3]}) 18. Rfc1 $1 $16 {[%cal Yg7h6,Ye3g2,Ga2a3,Gg3h4]} ({I played} 18. Rfe1 {which is an okay move, but the rook doesn’t do anything there. It’s much better to place him on c1, where he can later prevent any possible ...c4 idea.} Rxe3 19. fxe3 Qe7 20. Qd3 Re8 21. e4 Nd7 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Qe3 Ne5 24. Bg2 Bxg2 25. Kxg2 h3+ 26. Kg1 $16)) 17. Bf3 Nb7 18. h4 $1 {Not mentioned by Jones, but I believe this could be an interesting improvement over 18.Nce4 or 18.Rfe1. This move keeps the tension and waits for Black's plan. Most likely, Black will try} (18. Nec4 Na5 $1 {Black has no better option than to repeat moves here. He can't allow us to occupy the c4 square so easily, as this square is strategically important for our position.}) 18... Nd7 {aiming to exchange dark-squared bishops and take control over the dark squares.} 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Ne4 {This move is useful from several perspectives:  1. It centralizes the knight while also preventing any ...Rxe3 sacrifices.  2. Qb2 keeps the threat of controlling the a1-h8 diagonal.  3. 21.a3 is preparing to prevent ...a4 from Black, but also opens the a-file if it benefits us.  The most important idea in this position is that we need to play Rfc1! The rook belongs on c1 as it long-term prevents any future ...c4 ideas, which I allowed in the game against my student. The rook on e1 doesn't serve any special purpose, while on c1, it has many strategic roles.} a5 (20... Nf6 21. Ng5 a5 22. a3 Qe7 23. Rfc1 $1 Qe5 24. Kg2 Re7 25. Rb2 Nh7 (25... Ree8 26. Qb1 Re7 27. a4 Ba6 28. Nc4 Bxc4 29. Rxc4 Rae8 30. Rd2 $14 {/}) 26. Nh3 Nf6 27. Ra2 Ng4 $1 $132 (27... Ne4 28. axb4 Nxf2 29. Nxf2 Qxe3 30. bxa5 Rxa5 31. Rca1 Rxa2 32. Rxa2 $14 {[%cal Ga2a7,Gf2e4]})) 21. a3 Ne5 22. Bg2 Nd7 (22... Bd7 23. Ra1 Qe7 24. Qb2 f6 25. Rfc1 $13 {[%cal Ga1a2,Gb2a1]}) 23. Rfc1 $13 {We have a balanced position with roughly equal chances for both sides, but I believe it's slightly more pleasant from White's perspective.} *

