1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. O-O Nc6 (7... Nb6 {Definitely the most serious move to maintain equality, but Black needs to be deeply prepared. In many positions, Black must find precise engine moves to equalize, so I prefer White's side. We're playing on structure and understanding, where the engine isn't too important.} 8. e4 $5 (8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d5 Na5 10. e4 c6 11. Bf4 Bxc3 $1 {Very rare, but according to the engine, the best way to equalize the position.} (11... cxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Nc4 14. Rc1 $1 Nd6 15. Qd2 Bg4 16. Rfe1 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qd7 18. Qe2 Bf6 19. Bg4 Qb5 20. Qxb5 Nxb5 21. a4 Nd6 (21... Nd4 22. Kg2 $13) 22. Rc7 h5 23. Bd7 $16 {[%csl Gd7,Gf4][%cal Gb2b4];½-½ Svane,R (2610)-Blohberger,F (2439) AUT-chT 1920 Austria 2019 (5.3)}) 12. bxc3 cxd5 13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Nd4 Qc5 $1 15. Re1 Bd7 16. Re5 Qa3 $1 17. Qe1 $13 {[%cal Ge5e7,Gf4h6]}) 8... Bg4 $1 (8... Nc6 9. d5 Na5 10. Qe1 {Transposes to 7...Nc6.}) (8... c5 $2 9. d5 $1 e6 (9... Bg4 10. h3 $1 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 N8d7 12. Nc3 c4 13. Qe2 Ne5 14. Be3 Nd3 15. a4 Nd7 {½-½ Sasikiran,K (2668)-Sutovsky,E (2697) Olympiad-36 Mallorca 2004 (12)} 16. f4 $1 $18 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 10. Bg5 $1 f6 11. Be3 {[%csl Rc5]} Na6 12. Nc3 Nc4 13. Qe2 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 e5 15. Rfd1 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gg2f1]}) 9. d5 Qd7 $1 (9... c6 {Black's most common continuation.} 10. h3 $1 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 cxd5 12. exd5 N8d7 13. Nc3 Nc4 14. Rb1 $146 Nf6 $1 (14... Rc8 15. h4 $1 Nf6 16. Bh3 Rc5 17. Rd1 a6 18. b4 Rc7 19. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5]}) 15. Bf4 Rc8 16. Rfd1 $13 {With mutual chances.}) 10. Nc3 c6 11. Bf4 $5 cxd5 12. exd5 Na6 13. Qe1 $146 Rac8 14. Be5 $13 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gh2h3,Gd1d4,Ge1e4] White has a very interesting position, which the engine evaluates with the classic ''0.00.''}) 8. e4 Nb6 9. d5 Na5 10. Qe1 $1 {An important move. We immediately drive the knight away from a5 while keeping safe our knight on c3, avoiding the ...Bxc3 trade seen in the main line. The main line with 10.Nc3 leads nowhere for White, as 10...c6 11.Bf4 Bxc3! allows Black to equalize on the spot.} Nac4 11. Nc3 {[%cal Rg7c3]} e6 $1 (11... c6 $6 {The second most played move and a typical break in this structure. However, it fails here, as White keeps the initiative in the center and chases the knight from c4 across the entire board.} 12. b3 Nd6 (12... Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bh6 $1 Re8 15. Rc1 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge1d2,Gf1e1,Yh2h4,Yh4h5]}) 13. e5 $1 Nf5 (13... Nb5 $6 14. Nxb5 (14. dxc6 {is also fine for White.} Nxc3 15. Qxc3 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3];1-0 Amin,B (2636)-Kilic,E (2441) Julius Baer GenCup P/I m D3 Chess.com INT rapid 2024 (1.1)}) 14... cxb5 15. d6 $1 exd6 16. Bg5 $1 (16. Ba3 Re8 17. Bxd6 $16 {Granda Zuniga,J (2599)-Pereira,R (2418) Evora 2008}) 16... f6 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Qd2 Bd7 19. Rae1 $18 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gf3g5] After the dark-square bishops are traded, Ng5-Ne4 follows immediately. The bishop on g2 completely dominates the knight on b6. According to the engine, the evaluation is +1.60!}) 14. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf5]} (14. dxc6 bxc6 15. Qe4 $16 {Kurajica,B (2505)-Plenkovic,Z (2413) Zagreb 2014}) 14... Nh6 15. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh6] White has successfully executed his strategy. The knight on h6 is completely out of play and will remain inactive for a while.}) (11... e5 $6 {This is exactly the position we want to reach. Besides closing Black's dark-squared bishop, there is little benefit to this move. Now, b3-a4-Ba3 is the standard plan for White. The c5 square can also become a strong future outpost for us.} 12. b3 Nd6 13. a4 $16 {[%cal Gc1a3,Ga1c1,Ge1e3]}) 12. Bg5 $1 (12. b3 {The most played move by far offers nothing for White. After} Qf6 $1 13. bxc4 Qxc3 14. Qxc3 Bxc3 15. Rb1 Nxc4 $11 {Black easily equalizes.}) 12... f6 $1 (12... Qe8 $6 13. b3 $1 Nd6 14. e5 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gc3e4] Now, e4 and f6 will become strong outposts for our pieces!} Nf5 (14... exd5 15. exd6 Qxe1 16. Raxe1 Bxc3 17. Rc1 d4 18. dxc7 $18 {Mkrtchyan,M (2300)-Khachatryan,V (2007) Yerevan ARM 2022}) 15. dxe6 Bxe6 16. h3 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge5,Rg7][%cal Gg3g4,Gc3e4]}) 13. Bc1 $1 exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5 (14... Re8 $6 15. Qd1 Bg4 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 f5 18. Qb3 Kh8 19. a4 a5 20. h4 $16 {[%csl Yb6,Gc1,Yc4,Gd5,Gf3][%cal Gf1d1,Gc3b5] Gaal,Z (2298)-Atanasov,A (2148) Cala Gonone ITA 2022}) 15. Nd4 $1 Nxc3 16. Qxc3 Ne5 {We have reached an interesting position where it is not easy for White to prove compensation for the pawn. I believe the best way to maintain the initiative is} 17. Be3 $1 (17. Rd1 Bg4 (17... Re8) 18. f3 c5 $1 19. fxg4 cxd4 20. Rxd4 Qe7 21. Kh1 Rad8 $11) (17. f4 $5 Nf7 18. Be3 c6 19. Rad1 Qc7 20. f5 Re8 21. g4 $13 {[%csl Yc8,Yg7][%cal Gg1h1] ...also seems like an interesting way to play this position. Currently, both bishops are closed, and we can look for chances on the kingside. There's always the threat of g5 in the air. Black should be careful and play precisely to maintain equality.}) 17... c6 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge8f7]} 18. Rfe1 $1 {[%cal Rd8e8] Simply prevents ...Qe8 and prepares f4!} (18. Rad1 Qe8 19. h3 Qf7 $11 {½-½ Bryakin,M (2454)-Kalogridis,A (2328) Belgrade Serbia op 2023 (8)}) 18... Qd7 $1 ({Now} 18... Qe8 $2 {is not possible, as we simply win after} 19. f4 Ng4 20. Nxc6 $18 {[%csl Ge1,Re8][%cal Ge3c5]}) 19. f4 Ng4 20. Nxc6 $5 Nxe3 21. Rxe3 Kh8 $1 22. Rae1 $13 {[%cal Yd7c7,Yc6a5] I think we can conclude here. White definitely has a promising position. Na5 is a strong threat, while Black must find 22...Qd6 to fight for equality. We've already gone too far, and it won't be easy for Black to find all these moves, especially after 17.Be3, where there is only one game in the database!} *

