1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 dxc4 8. e4 b5 $1 (8... Bg4 {Black's idea is to play ...e5 followed by ...Nfd7.} 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e5 {Black's most common continuation. Besides this move, Black has also tried two other interesting options.} (10... Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gb4d3]} 11. e5 Nd5 12. Qe2 {[%csl Rc4]} Nac7 (12... Nab4 13. Qxc4 $16) 13. h4 {Always a good move when there’s no knight on f6. If we succeed in opening the h-file, Ne4-Ng5 could become a really dangerous threat for Black.} h5 14. a4 Qd7 (14... b5 15. Bg2 $5 $13 {[%cal Gg3g4]}) 15. Rd1 Rad8 (15... f6 $1 16. Ne4 $1 $36) 16. Qxc4 Ne6 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Qb3 $16 {½-½ Matlakov,M (2688)-Antipov,M (2596) RUS-ch Higher League 74th Cheboksary 2021 (8)}) (10... e6 $6 11. h4 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gh4h5]}) 11. dxe5 Nfd7 (11... Qxd1 $2 {would be a big mistake since after} 12. Bxd1 Nfd7 {we can defend our pawn with} 13. f4 $16) 12. e6 $1 {is a logical move, returning the pawn but damaging Black's structure. Our future ideas include f4 and e5.} fxe6 13. Be3 Qe7 (13... Ne5 $5 {[%cal Ge5f2,Ge5d3]} 14. Be2 Nd3 {The most common move.} (14... Na6 15. Qa4 Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 16. Rad1 $146 b5 17. Qc2 $13 {[%cal Ga2a3] With chances for both sides.}) 15. Bxd3 cxd3 $1 (15... Qxd3 16. Qg4 $1 Qd7 17. e5 Bxe5 {½-½ Tabatabaei,M (2655)-Kacharava,N (2532) Elllobregat op 3rd Sant Boi de Llobregat 2022 (7)} 18. Rad1 $1 Qf7 19. Bh6 Bg7 20. Bxg7 Qxg7 21. Qxc4 $44 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf1e1]}) 16. Qb3 Nd7 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. f4 Bxc3 $6 (18... g5 $1 {is a very strong move, and the only one to stay in the game!} 19. Rxd3 gxf4 20. gxf4 Kh8 $1 21. Qd1 Nf6 22. Kh2 $13 {[%csl Ye6][%cal Gd1f3] I believe it's much easier to play from White's perspective.}) 19. Qxc3 e5 20. Qxd3 $16 {1-0 Tabatabaei,M (2551)-Ghaem Maghami,E (2596) Wch Blitz Almaty 2022 (18)}) 14. Bg2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5]} Na6 $1 (14... Ne5 $2 {An interesting move, but a mistake. The knight may seem stable on d3 for now, but after we shut down the g7-bishop, b3 will cut it off.} 15. f4 $1 Nd3 16. e5 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc3e4]} Nd7 {Tabatabaei,M (2677)-Vidit,S (2730) chess.com INT 2023} 17. b3 $1 {[%csl Rd3]} Nb6 18. Qe2 Nd5 19. Ne4 Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Nb4 21. Qc5 Qxc5+ 22. Nxc5 cxb3 23. axb3 $16 {[%csl Gc5,Re6,Gg2,Rg7][%cal Gc5b7,Gc5e6]}) (14... Nc5 $6 {is another logical route to d3, but even a strong GM like Sindarov can overlook a resource like} 15. e5 $1 Bxe5 16. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga1e1]} Ncd7 17. Qxc4 Nb6 18. Qb3 Na6 19. Rfe1 Bg7 {Tabatabaei,M (2664)-Sindarov,J (2629) Abu Dhabi UAE 2022} 20. Rad1 $1 $14 {[%csl Ge3,Re6,Gg2] /}) 15. Qe2 Nb4 16. Qxc4 Nc2 17. Nd5 $1 cxd5 18. Qxc2 d4 19. Bd2 Rac8 20. Qb3 {It looks like good preparation from Carlsen. According to the engine, the position is very close to equal, but practically speaking, it’s very unpleasant for Black. It’s much easier to play from White’s perspective due to the bishop pair.} Nc5 21. Qa3 Qd7 22. Rac1 b6 23. e5 {[%csl Gg2] White sacrifices a pawn to open the g2-bishop's diagonal and activate the rook on e1.} {Up until this point, both players have played very well. Here, Mamedyarov had the chance to play some tough engine moves to equalize the position. It's move 23, highlighting how deeply Black needs to be prepared for positions like this.} Bxe5 (23... Qa4 $1 24. f4 Qxa3 25. bxa3 g5 $1 $132) 24. Rfe1 Bg7 25. b4 Na4 26. Rxc8 Rxc8 27. Qb3 Nc3 28. Rxe6 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2][%cal Gg2f1,Gh3h4] /. Carlsen,M (2864)-Mamedyarov,S (2759) Stavanger NOR 2022}) 9. Qe2 {This is the starting position of our 7.Nc3 system. Black has many different options, and I'll try to present you with a lot of interesting ideas against Black's five main choices.} b4 (9... Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e5] With the same ideas as in 8...Bg4.} 10. e5 Nd5 11. a4 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5d3] A critical position, played by two strong GMs. The idea is to play ...Bd3.} (11... b4 12. Ne4 c3 13. bxc3 bxc3 14. a5 $1 {[%cal Rd8a5]} Qc8 $6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 15. Ra3 $1 Qa6 16. Qe1 (16. Nxc3 {The endgame is also fine.} Qxe2 17. 