ne a human would play it.} 12. Bf4 Nbd7 (12... b4 13. Na4 $14 {[%cal Ga4c5]}) (12... Nfd7 13. e5 Nb6 14. Ng5 $13 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gh2h4]}) 13. d5 cxd5 14. e5 b4 (14... Nh5 $6 15. Rxd5 $1 Nxf4 16. gxf4 {[%cal Gg2a8]} Rb8 17. Rxb5 Qa7 18. a4 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Rc4][%cal Yd7b6,Yf3d4] /}) 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Na4 Bg4 $1 {looks like a very dangerous line for Black, but according to the engine, it leads to forced equality.} (16... Bf5 17. Ne5 Qb5 $1 18. b3 {Interesting, unclear position. 18...Rfb8 is on the edge of equality, while 18...Rab8 is 0.60 for White.}) 17. axb4 axb4 18. Nc5 Qc6 19. Qxe7 Rfe8 20. Ne5 Bxd1 21. Qxf7+ Kh8 22. Rxa8 Qxa8 23. Ne6 Rxe6 24. Qxe6 Qe8 25. Bxd5 Qxe6 26. Bxe6 c3 27. bxc3 bxc3 $11) 12. e5 Nd5 13. h4 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) (10... Qe8 {Tsvetkov,A (2407)-Yeletsky,I (2494) Sochi RUS 2023} 11. a3 Na6 12. Bf4 $13 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gh2h4]}) (10... a4 {[%cal Ga4a3] Black threat to play ...a3.} 11. a3 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 e5 $1 14. dxe5 Nfd7 15. Bg2 Qe7 16. f4 Nc5 {Pechac,J (2580)-Kadric,D (2584) Austria AUT 2023} 17. e6 $1 {Important move! We want to play e4-e5 and activate our g2-bishop.} fxe6 (17... Qxe6 18. e5 {[%cal Gc3b5]} Nd3 (18... Nb3 19. Rb1 Nxc1 20. Rbxc1 Ra7 21. Qe3 Rd7 22. Rxd7 Qxd7 (22... Nxd7 $6 23. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gd1d8]}) 23. h4 $44) 19. Nxb5 cxb5 20. Bxa8 Nc6 21. Bxc6 Qxc6 22. Rf1 Re8 23. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3]} Nxb2 24. Qg2 Qe6 25. Rab1 Qd7 $3 (25... c3 $6 26. Bxc3 Nc4 27. Rbe1 Nxa3 28. Bb4 Qb6+ (28... Nc4 29. Qb7 $16 {[%csl Rb5]}) 29. Qf2 Qxf2+ 30. Rxf2 Nc4 31. Kg2 Bf8 32. Rb1 {[%cal Gg2f3,Gf3e4,Gf2a2]}) 26. Bc3 Nd3 27. Kh2 Bf8 28. Ra1 $13 {[%cal Ga1a2,Gh3h4]}) 18. e5 {[%csl Rg7]} g5 $1 (18... Nb3 19. Be3 Nxa1 20. Rxa1 {[%csl Ya4,Ra8,Yb5,Rb8,Yc4,Yc6,Rg7][%cal Gc3b5,Gc3e4,Gh3h4]}) 19. Rd6 (19. Nxb5 Nb3 $132) 19... gxf4 (19... Nb7 20. Ne4 gxf4 21. Bxf4 Nxd6 22. exd6 Qe8 23. Ng5) 20. Bxf4 Nd3 21. Rd1 Ra7 22. Ne4 {[%cal Gf4g5,Gh3h4]}) 11. d5 $1 {Crucial and most concrete idea here.} (11. e5 Nd5 12. e6 N7b6 13. exf7+ Rxf7 14. Ne5 Bxe5 15. dxe5 Bf5 $15 {½-½ Esipenko,A (2668)-Ivic,V (2553) Wch U20 59th Cala Gonone 2022 (8)}) 11... cxd5 12. e5 b4 {Only move for Black.} 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Nb5 {It's a very unclear position with few games in the database. Both sides have playable options. While it seems easier for me to play with the White pieces, I believe the more prepared player will gain the upper hand.} (14. Na4 $6 e6 (14... Bd7 $1 15. Nc5 Bg4 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg4f3,Ge7e6]}) 15. Be3 Bd7 (15... Qc7 $1 16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Nxc8 Rbxc8 18. Bf4 Qc5 19. h4 $13 {[%cal Ga1c1]}) 16. Nc5 Rc8 17. Bd4 Qe7 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ga2a3] Warmerdam,M (2636)-Adhiban,B (2551) Douglas IOM 2023}) 14... e6 {The most logical move, consolidating the position.} (14... Ba6 15. a4 e6 (15... Re8 $2 16. Ne5 $1 Bxb5 17. axb5 Qb6 $2 18. Rxd5 $1 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 $18 {Mayrhuber,N (2101)-Weichhart,D (1949) Vienna AUT 2022}) 16. Be3 $13 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf3d4]}) (14... Bd7 15. Nbd4 Ne4 (15... Rc8 16. Ne5 e6 17. Bf3 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gc1f4] /}) 16. Bf4 $13) 15. a4 Ba6 (15... Bd7 $5 16. Be3 Bxb5 17. axb5 Qb8 18. Nd4 Re8 19. b3 e5 20. Nc6 Qxb5 21. Na7 Qb7 22. bxc4 Rxa7 23. Bxa7 Qxa7 24. cxd5 e4 $1 25. d6 $1 $13 {[%cal Ge2b5] a complicated position where, if Black plays a few more engine moves, the position should be fully equalized.}) 16. Nfd4 Bxb5 17. axb5 a4 $1 (17... Re8 $6 {a logical move, but a mistake! It highlights just how difficult the position is to play.} 18. b3 $1 cxb3 19. Ra4 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rb4][%cal Gd4b3]} Nd7 20. Nxb3 $16 {Carlsen,M (2859)-Mamedyarov,S (2741) chess24.com INT 2022}) (17... b3 18. Be3 (18. Ra4 Re8 $1 19. Be3 Qb8 $1 20. g4 e5 21. Nxb3 Qxb5 22. g5 Qxa4 23. Nc5 Qb4 24. gxf6 d4 25. Bxa8 dxe3 26. Ne4 Rxa8 27. fxg7 $13) 18... Qc7 19. b6 Qd7 20. Nf3 Qb5 $1 21. Ne5 Ra6 22. Ra3 $13 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ge3d4]}) 18. Nc6 Qb6 19. Nxb4 Qxb5 20. Bd2 Nd7 (20... Rad8 {Would lead to an equal position for Black.} 21. h4 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gg2f3]} h5 $1 (21... Rfe8 $6 {would be a very dangerous move for Black.} 22. Bc3 h5 23. Qe5 $14 {[%cal Gg2f3,Gg1g2,Ga1a2] /}) 22. Nc2 Ng4 $1 23. Bc3 e5 24. Na3 Qc5 $11) 21. Bc3 Nc5 22. h4 Nb3 (22... h5 23. g4 $36) {So far, we've been following the game Carlsen - Firouzja, where Firouzja demonstrated amazing, deep preparation. Here, I would suggest} 23. Ra2 {[%cal Gg2d5,Gh4h5] where we threat several ideas, including Bxd5 and h5.} (23. Bxg7 Kxg7 24. Qe5+ f6 25. Qxe6 Qxb4 26. Rxd5 Ra7 27. Rad1 Re7 28. Rd7 Rff7 29. Rxe7 Rxe7 30. Rd7 Rxd7 31. Qxd7+ Kh6 32. Bd5 Qe1+ 33. Kg2 Nd2 $11 {Carlsen,M (2830)-Firouzja,A (2760) chess.com INT 2024}) 23... h5 $1 {It seems like the only good move for Black.} (23... Rfe8 $6 24. h5 $16 {[%cal Gh5h6]}) (23... Ra7 24. Nc2 {[%cal Gh4h5]} h5 $1 25. g4 $1 {Black is already under significant pressure.}) {Here, White has a few good options. I believe a simple} 24. Nc2 {[%cal Rd5d4,Gg3g4] keeps the tension on the board. If Black allows it, our next move will be 25.g4.}) (9... Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gb4d3]} 10. Rd1 Nb4 11. Ne1 $5 {[%cal Ga2a3,Rb4d3]} (11. a4 Bd7 12. Ne5 a6 {1-0 Carlsen,M (2864)-Saric,I (2680) Zagreb SuperUnited Blitz 2022 (9)} 13. Be3 $13 {[%cal Gd4d5]}) 11... Bg4 $1 12. f3 Be6 $1 {a classic engine move. Black is waiting for b3, and after all exchanges on d3, he can play ...Bb3!} 13. Be3 Qc8 14. g4 $13 {At some point, we will play a3. In the meantime, we can improve our position with moves like Qf2 and Rd2. The engine recommends ...h5 for Black, but practically, it looks like a dangerous move. We can simply play h3, with no real danger for us, while Black's king would be open and vulnerable.}) (9... Bb7 $6 10. e5 $1 Nd5 11. a4 Na6 12. h4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gh4h5]}) 10. Nd1 Ba6 (10... a5 {would be a slower option for Black.} 11. Re1 Ba6 12. e5 Nd5 13. h4 $36 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ge5e6]} e6 (11... c5 12. d5 Nbd7 (12... c3 $6 13. Qc2 cxb2 (13... e6 $1 14. dxe6 fxe6 15. bxc3 Nc6 16. Ng5 Re8 17. e5 Nd5 18. f4 $13 {[%csl Rg7] an unclear position with all three possible results.}) 14. Bxb2 c4 15. Bd4 $16 Qa5 16. Ne3 Nbd7 17. Nxc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Rac8 19. Qe2 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge4,Gg2][%cal Gg2h3] Petkov,M (2497)-Lashkin,J (2451) Chisinau MDA 2024}) 13. e5 Nxd5 14. e6 N7b6 $1 15. exf7+ Rxf7 16. Ng5 $13 {[%cal Gg5e6,Ge6g7] Fressinet,L (2643)-Aradhya,G (2344) chess.com INT 2023} (16. a3 $5 {would also be an interesting try for White, as Black needs to find a series of precise engine moves to reach an equal endgame, which seems fine according to the engine but is not so clear to human eyes.} b3 $1 17. Ng5 Rf5 18. Qe6+ Kh8 19. a4 $5 Bc8 20. Nf7+ Rxf7 21. Qxf7 a5 $1 $11)) (11... Nfd7 $2 12. e5 $1 Nb6 {Even though Fressinet played a good move, I would recommend the move we've seen many times in this variation.} 13. h4 $1 (13. Qe4 Nd5 14. Qh4 f6 15. Ne3 Nxe3 16. Bxe3 $16 {Fressinet,L (2624)-Bacrot,E (2648) Albi FRA 2022}) 13... c3 14. Qe4 cxb2 15. Nxb2 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5,Ge4h4]}) 12. e5 {The most logical continuation for White.} (12. Ne3 $5 {½-½ Oparin,G (2676)-Brkic,A (2639) Saint Louis Summer-A 2024 (6)} Nxe4 13. Nc2 Nd6 14. Nxb4 Nf5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6] looks fine for Black.}) 12... Nd5 13. Ne3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] We've reached an interesting position with only one game in the database! Our plan will be the standard h4-h5, aiming for a kingside attack. I believe White has solid compensation, and the position is rich with ideas.} c3 (13... Nd7 14. h4 Nxe3 15. Bxe3 c5 $1 {Only move for Black to maintain the equality.} 16. h5 $36 cxd4 17. Bxd4 Rc8 (17... Qb8 $6 {[%csl Gb4,Re5]} 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Ng5 $18 {[%cal Ge2g4]}) 18. Qd2 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gh5h6]} gxh5 {is not an easy move for a human to play!} 19. Qxb4 Qc7 20. Rac1 $13 {[%csl Yg8][%cal Gb2b3] an unclear but playable position for both sides!}) 14. Qc2 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5]} (14... Nd7 {looks like a normal human move, which allows us a solid advantage after} 15. bxc3 bxc3 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Qxc3 {[%csl Yd5,Yd7,Ye6]} Rc8 18. Qa3 Bc4 $2 (18... Rc6 $1 19. h4 $13 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf3h2,Gh2g4]}) 19. Bg5 $1 Qb6 20. Qe3 Rb8 $6 21. h4 $16 {[%cal Gg5h6,Gh4h5,Gf3h2,Gh2g4] Berczes,D (2400)-Mamatov,M (2362) Budapest HUN 2024} (21. Be7 $1 Rfc8 22. Bd6 Rb7 23. Nd2 Ba6 24. h4 $16 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gh4h5,Ge1c1]})) 15. h4 $1 c5 $1 (15... Nd7 16. h5 $14) 16. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} Nc6 (16... Rd8 17. h6 Bf8 18. dxc5 Nc6 {0-1 Epinoux,J (2183)-Artner,M (2148) W-ch WS/M/890 email ICCF email 2023} 19. Ng5 $1 Bxc5 20. Nxd5 exd5 21. e6 $13) 17. h6 Bh8 18. dxc5 {[%csl Rh8] It's a new, complex position, with the engine suggesting many possible moves. It seems playable for both sides. In conclusion, 7.Nc3 is a fresh and interesting approach that offers a dynamic and promising way to challenge the symmetrical Grünfeld. There's still plenty of room for improvement on both sides, but at least Black doesn't have a forced line to equalize, as in many other variations. The position is rich with ideas, creating significant practical challenges for Black, and it requires deep preparation from him to maintain equality.} *

