{[%evp 0,46,29,27,21,-2,42,37,35,-2,14,19,19,11,8,-12,-15,-23,-21,-29,-19,-20,38,13,41,13,69,84,84,27,81,47,82,50,58,98,132,18,34,43,43,26,26,29,23,22,32,39,69]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c6 5. Bg2 d5 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 $5 (7... Nbd7 $6 {[%csl Yc6,Yd5,Yd7] It's very important to remember that in this structure, it's never good to play Nbd7.} 8. cxd5 $1 cxd5 {[%csl Gc6,Rd7][%cal Gd7c6] The knight on d7 is poorly placed; it belongs on c6.} 9. Bf4 a6 10. Qb3 $1 e6 {[%csl Yd5,Yd7,Ye6]} 11. Rfc1 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Yc3a4,Ya4c5] Here, we will simply continue with a4-a5. If Black tries to prevent it with ...b6, we will prepare Na2-Nb4 in the future, with the idea of exploiting the c6 square!}) (7... Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb8d7] One of the best alternatives for Black. He can continue development with ...Nbd7, while also preparing to support the ...Ne4 jump.} 8. Ne5 Nbd7 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 $1 (10... Nxd7 $2 11. cxd5 Bxd4 12. e4 $18 {Kourkoulos Arditis,S (2535)-Koutlas,N (2314) Kavala GRE 2022}) 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Bxd4 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Rd1 Bf6 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7 17. Rxd7 Rfd8 18. Rxd8 Rxd8 19. Be3 {We have a good chance to win this endgame, but objectively, Black has good chance to hold the draw.}) (7... e6 $2 {[%csl Rc8] Closing the bishop on c8 like this doesn't make strategic sense for Black.} 8. Bf4 $1 Re8 (8... dxc4 9. e4 b5 10. Re1 a5 11. h4 $16 {[%cal Ya5a4,Ya2a3,Ga1d1,Gd1c2]}) 9. c5 Nbd7 10. Rc1 b6 11. b4 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Ya7a5,Yb4b5] /. We will continue with h4, and if Black plays 11...a5, we respond with 12.b5!}) (7... Re8 $5 8. Qb3 Qb6 (8... dxc4 9. Qxc4 Nbd7 10. Rd1 Nb6 11. Qb3 Be6 12. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 9. Bf4 $1 dxc4 10. Qxc4 Be6 11. Qd3 Nd5 (11... Nbd7 12. e4 $16) 12. Bg5 $14) (7... a6 8. Qb3 e6 {Here, we have the same situation as after 7...e6, but with an additional a6 included.} (8... b5 $6 {[%csl Rc5] wouldn't be a good strategic choice, as after} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. a4 $1 {we break the queenside structure, seize control of the c5 square, and apply pressure on the a6 pawn.} (10. Bg5 e6 (10... Bb7 11. a4 Ne4 12. h4 Nxg5 13. hxg5 Nc6 14. axb5 axb5 15. Qxb5 Rb8 16. e3 $14 {/}) 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nd2 Nbd7 13. Ndxe4 Rb8 14. Bf4 e5 15. dxe5 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe5 17. Rad1 $14 {[%cal Yd8c7,Yb3a3,Ge4c3,Gc3d5] /}) 10... bxa4 11. Nxa4 {[%csl Gb6,Gc5,Ge5]} Nc6 12. Bf4 Nh5 13. Be3 Bg4 14. Rfd1 Rb8 15. Qc3 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rh5][%cal Ga4c5,Gb2b3] /}) (8... dxc4 $6 {would also provide us with a strong pawn structure and control of the center.} 9. Qxc4 Bg4 10. Qb3 Qc8 {Ding,L (2711)-Kamsky,G (2721) Antalya 2013} 11. e4 $1 {would be the only thing I would change from this game. We immediately take control of the center.} c5 (11... a5 12. Be3 Na6 13. a3 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf3e5]}) 12. dxc5 Nbd7 13. e5 Nxc5 14. Qa3 Nfd7 15. Nd5 Kh8 16. Be3 $1 Bxf3 (16... Ne6 $2 17. Nd2 {[%csl Rg4]} Qd8 (17... Nxe5 18. Nb6 $18) 18. f3 Bh5 19. g4 Nxe5 20. gxh5 Qxd5 21. h6 $1 Bf6 22. f4 Nc4 23. Bxd5 Nxa3 24. bxa3 Bxa1 25. Rxa1 $18) 17. Bxf3 Nxe5 18. Be2 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rc5,Rc8][%cal Ga1c1,Gd5b6]}) 9. Bf4 $1 Nbd7 10. Rad1 $16) (7... b6 $6 8. Ne5 Bb7 9. Qa4 $1 e6 10. Rd1 h6 (10... Nfd7 {is the typical way to remove the knight from e5, but it doesn't work here, since after} 11. cxd5 $1 cxd5 (11... Nxe5 $6 12. dxe5 cxd5 13. e4 Nc6 14. exd5 Nxe5 15. dxe6 Qe7 16. Nd5 Qxe6 17. Bg5 $1 Bc6 18. Qa3 Kh8 19. Rac1 $16 {[%csl Ga3,Gc1,Gd1,Gd5,Gg2,Gg5]}) {we have a strong} 12. e4 dxe4 (12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 {transpose to 11...Nxe5}) 13. Nxe4 Bd5 14. Be3 a6 15. Rac1 b5 16. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Ya8,Yb8,Gc1,Gc2,Gd1,Ge4,Ge5][%cal Gh2h4,Ge3f4] We have better development, control over the c-file, and harmoniously placed pieces.}) 11. h4 $14 {[%cal Gc1f4]}) 8. h4 $1 $146 {[%cal Gh4h5] Always a useful move, especially when the knight is not on f6.} (8. Qb3 $14) 8... Nxc3 (8... Bg4 9. Qb3 $16 {[%cal Gc1f4]}) (8... Nf6 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf3e5]}) 9. bxc3 dxc4 10. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6]} c5 11. h6 {[%csl Gh6] Now, the pawn on h6 becomes a major problem for Black for the rest of the game!} Bf6 (11... Bh8 {[%csl Gh8]} 12. Qa4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gc1e3]}) 12. d5 $5 (12. Bg5 $14) 12... Bxc3 13. Rb1 Bh8 14. Bf4 c3 15. e4 Na6 16. Be5 $14 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gd1b3,Gb3c3] With Qb3, we will capture the pawn on c3, trade off the dark-squared bishops, and the pawn on h6 will become a key factor in our play, constantly preparing mating nets around Black's king.} *

