1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 c6 6. O-O d5 7. Re1 $5 {This interesting move was recently played in the World Championship match between Gukesh and Ding.} dxc4 (7... Ne4 $5 {is one of the most solid moves for Black!} 8. Bf4 $146 (8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 dxc4 10. Bg5 Re8 11. Qc1 $13) 8... Bf5 9. Nc3 dxc4 $1 (9... e6 $6 10. Nh4 $1 Nd7 11. Nxf5 gxf5 12. e3 {[%cal Gc3e4]} Nxc3 13. bxc3 dxc4 14. Qb1 Nb6 15. Qb4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gf4,Gg2][%cal Ga2a4]}) (9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Nd2 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Nd7 12. Nxc4 e5 13. dxe5 Be6 14. Qd4 {[%cal Ge1d1] White has a slightly more pleasant position.}) 10. Ne5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Be6 $1 12. Nf3 Qa5 13. Qc2 $13 {[%cal Ge1b1,Ga2a4] With mutual chances.}) (7... Nbd7 {[%csl Yc6,Yd5,Rd7] It's very important to remember that in this structure, it's never good to play Nbd7.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 {[%csl Gc6,Rd7][%cal Gd7c6] The knight on d7 is poorly placed; it belongs on c6.} 9. Bf4 Nb6 10. Nbd2 h6 (10... Bf5 11. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gd1b3]}) 11. Rc1 Bf5 (11... g5 $6 12. Bc7 Qd7 13. h4 $16) 12. h4 $14 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gc1c5] stopping ...g5, so we can proceed with Qb3 and Rc5.}) ({One of Black's most solid options could be} 7... Bf5 8. Qb3 Qb6 9. Nc3 Rd8 10. h3 {all three games went} Ne4 $6 {1-0 Svane,R (2615)-Bortnyk,O (2598) Titled Arena May 8th Lichess.org INT blitz 2021} (10... Qxb3 {results in a balanced position with roughly equal chances for both sides.} 11. axb3 h6 12. Bd2 $13 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gd2b4]} (12. Bf4 $13 {[%cal Gf4c7]})) 11. g4 $1 {Critical position for Black.} Qxb3 $1 (11... Be6 12. Bf4 Na6 $6 {1-0 Sasikiran,K (2666)-Akash,G (2343) IND-ch 51st Jalgaon 2013 (3)} 13. e3 $1 $146 (13. c5 Qxb3 14. axb3 $14 {[%cal Ga1a4,Gb3b4]}) 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 dxc4 15. Qa4 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Rd5 16. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gf3g5,Ge3e4]}) 12. axb3 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Be4 14. Ba3 e6 {½-½ Gordievsky,D (2592)-Hakobyan,A (2559) Saint Louis Summer-C 2019 (1)} 15. Bc5 $5 {[%csl Ra7]} a6 16. Ne5 f6 $1 (16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Nd7 18. Be7 Re8 19. Nxd7 Rxe7 20. Nb6 Rd8 21. e3 {[%cal Gf2f4]} e5 22. b4 $14) 17. Nd3 Nd7 18. Be7 Rdc8 19. f3 Bxd3 20. exd3 $13 {[%csl Gb3,Gc3,Gc4,Gd3,Gd4,Ge7,Gg2,Yg7] One of the most interesting pawn structures I've ever seen. We have a slightly better position, and the bishop pair definitely helps us reinforce that advantage.}) 8. e4 Bg4 (8... Na6 $146 {[%cal Ga6b4,Gb4d3] aiming for Nb4-Nd3. We can respond with} 9. Na3 {gaining tempo to transfer the knight to c2 and continue with our original plan on the kingside.} b5 (9... Be6 10. Ng5 Bg4 11. f3 Bc8 12. Nxc4 Nd7 13. f4 Nb6 14. Ne5 c5 15. dxc5 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Nxc5 17. Ngxf7 Rxf7 18. Nxf7 Kxf7 19. Be3 Bxb2 (19... Bg4 20. Bxc5 Bxb2 21. Rab1 Bxd1 22. Rxd1 Rc8 23. Bf2) 20. Bxc5 Bxa1 21. Rxa1 {[%csl Gc5,Gg2]}) 10. Nc2 {[%cal Ra6b4]} (10. b3 c3 $15) 10... Bb7 (10... c5 11. a4 b4 12. d5 b3 $1 13. Na3 Nb4 14. Ne5 Ba6 15. Nexc4 Bxc4 16. Nxc4 Nc2 17. Bf4 Nd7 18. e5 Nb6 19. Ne3 Nxa1 20. Qxa1 $44 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] A long engine line where Black is completely fine, but White seems to have interesting compensation due to the strong d5-e5 pawns. The next idea will be h4-h5. We have a balanced position with roughly equal chances for both sides.}) 11. a4 Nc7 12. h4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gh4h5] Preparing our original plan.} a6 13. e5 Nd7 (13... Nfd5 14. h5 $14 {[%cal Gf3h4,Yh5h6]}) 14. Ng5 $13 {[%cal Gh4h5] White has a promising position, rich with ideas, while Black remains solid.}) (8... b5 $5 {Recently played by MVL in a rapid game against Carlsen, this move appears to be a reasonable choice.} 9. a4 a5 10. axb5 cxb5 11. Nc3 Bb7 {1-0 Carlsen,M (2831)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2731) Oslo CCT Final KO 2024 (1.3)} (11... b4 12. Na4 Bd7 13. Bf4 $13) {Here, instead of 12.d5, which was Carlsen's choice, I would suggest} 12. e5 {with the same idea as in the main line - removing the knight to prepare opening the kingside with h4-h5.} Nd5 13. Nxb5 Nb4 14. Re2 N8a6 15. Nc3 Nc7 16. h4 $13 {[%csl Ya5,Yc4][%cal Gh4h5,Gc1g5]}) 9. Nbd2 {According to the engine, the best move is} b5 $1 $146 {but after} (9... c5 $5 {seems like a human reaction. Ding wants to break the center with ..c5 followed by ..e6.} 10. d5 e6 11. Nxc4 $1 {White claims a small but stable advantage due to the future passed d-pawn and the strong bishop on g2.} Nbd7 (11... exd5 12. exd5 Nbd7 (12... Qxd5 13. Qxd5 Nxd5 14. Ng5 $1 Nb4 15. Bxb7 Nc2 16. Bxa8 (16. Nxf7 $5 Nxe1 17. Nh6+ Bxh6 18. Bxh6 Nf3+ 19. Kg2 Nd7 $1 20. Bd5+ Kh8 21. h3 Bxh3+ 22. Kxh3 Rab8 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. Kg2 Nd4 $11) 16... Nxe1 17. Be4 $14 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc4d6,Gc1e3]}) 13. d6 $1 $14) 12. h3 exd5 13. exd5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 b5 15. Na3 Qb6 16. Bf4 Rfe8 17. Qd2 Rad8 18. Nc2 $14 {½-½ Gukesh,D (2783)-Ding,L (2728) World-ch Ding-Gukesh Singapore 2024 (7)}) 10. h3 {It seems difficult even for such a great player as Ding Liren to find an engine move like} Bc8 $5 (10... Bxf3 $6 11. Nxf3 a5 12. e5 Nd5 13. h4 $1 Na6 14. h5 $36 {}) 11. a4 a5 12. Nf1 {Seems like one of the most reasonable ideas for White: transferring the knight to e3, from where it can support the kingside attack. The h4-h5 push will be a crucial idea for us.} Nbd7 13. Ne3 Nb6 14. Qc2 Qc7 (14... Nxa4 $6 {wouldn't be the most precise, as we have} 15. Nxc4 $1) (14... bxa4 15. Nxc4 Be6 16. Nce5 Bb3 17. Qxc6 Nfd7 18. Nxd7 Nxd7 19. h4 $13 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg2h3,Gc1g5] with an interesting position for both sides.}) (14... Ba6 15. h4 $5 {Once again, the best chance to play for a win. We stick to our original plan with e5, followed by h5, aiming to open the kingside.} (15. axb5 {forces simplifications, leading to an equal position.} cxb5 (15... Bxb5 $2) 16. Rxa5 Bb7 17. Rxb5 Nxe4 $1 18. Nxc4 Rc8 19. b3 Nd6 20. Rc5 Bxf3 21. Bxf3 Nbxc4 22. bxc4 Bxd4 23. Rxc8 Qxc8 24. Rxe7 Nxc4 $11) 15... b4 16. e5 b3 $1 {An important move, preventing Qe4-Qh4.} (16... Nfd5 $2 17. h5 $1 {[%cal Gc2e4]}) 17. Qd1 Nfd5 18. h5 Nb4 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gb4d3]} 19. Bf1 Nd3 20. Bxd3 cxd3 21. Bd2 Qd7 {[%cal Gf8b8]} 22. Rc1 Nxa4 23. Qxb3 Bb5 24. d5 Rab8 25. hxg6 hxg6 26. Bxa5 c5 27. Bd2 $13) 15. Bd2 Bb7 16. h4 $5 $36 {Gukesh likely had a similar idea when preparing this line against Ding. After sacrificing the pawn, White's only reasonable plan is to initiate a kingside attack, while Black's pieces are drawn to the queenside, limiting his counterplay} e6 (16... h5 $6 {would allow us to seize a strong initiative after} 17. e5 Nfd5 18. Ng5 c5 $1 19. Nf5 $1 {In my opinion, from a practical standpoint, this position already looks dangerous for Black.} cxd4 20. Nxd4 b4 21. Nge6 $13 {As a result, White will win some material, but due to Black's active pieces and strong queenside structure, he has enough compensation to maintain equality.}) (16... h6 $2 {would be a terrible mistake, as after} 17. e5 Nfd5 18. h5 g5 19. Nf5 $18 {[%cal Gf5h6,Gd2g5] White's attack becomes unstoppable.}) 17. axb5 cxb5 18. e5 Nfd5 19. Bxa5 $44 {[%cal Gh4h5] White has regained the pawn and is preparing h5 to open the kingside. With the h-file open, plans like Ng5 followed by Qe4-Qh4 become significant threats. Objectively, 7.Re1!? leads to sharp, complex lines that require practical experience to navigate.} *

