{[%evp 0,47,21,11,9,20,40,13,38,20,24,21,17,15,12,24,33,202,41,48,48,67,43,17,59,5,77,43,30,16,224,69,46,-11,122,18,8,-13,-258,-18,-15,-61,-65,-25,-36,-26,43,-4,-70,0]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c5 5. d5 $5 b5 {The best try by Black. In Benko style, he opens the queenside.} 6. cxb5 a6 7. bxa6 O-O 8. Nc3 d6 9. Bg2 Nxa6 $1 (9... Nbd7 10. O-O Nb6 11. Re1 Bxa6 12. Bf4 (12. h3 $5 {looks like a solid alternative for us. According to the engine, Black needs to find a lot of precise moves to achieve active play!} Qc7 $1 (12... Nfd7 $6 {is a typical move in this type of position. It allows us to play a nice strategic maneuver.} 13. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2b1]} Ra7 $5 {[%cal Gd8a8]} (13... Nc4 $2 {McFarland,R (2215)-Mangione,C (2074) England 2010} 14. Nxc4 Bxc4 15. Bd2 Qa5 16. Qc1 $16 {[%cal Gb2b3]}) 14. Ndb1 $1 Qa8 15. Qc2 Rb8 16. a3 Nc4 17. b3 {[%csl Ga3,Gb3]} Na5 18. Nd2 Rab7 19. Rb1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Ge2e3,Gg1h2,Gf2f4,Yc3a2,Yb3b4] /. We succeeded in our plan - the queenside is defended. Now we will slowly improve our position with Kh2, followed by e3-f4, controlling d4 and e5, from where real problems for Black will begin.}) 13. Bg5 (13. Nh2 $5 {[%cal Gh2f1,Gf1e3]} Nc4 14. Nf1 Nd7 15. Nd2 Na3 $1 $132 {[%csl Ya1,Yc1,Yc3]}) 13... h6 14. Bf4 g5 $6 (14... Rab8 15. Rb1 $14) 15. Bc1 $1 e6 16. dxe6 fxe6 {Vernay,C (2449)-Ivanisevic,I (2617) Aix les Bains 2011} 17. e4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Nc4 (17... Qf7 18. Bxg5 hxg5 19. Nxg5 Qe7 20. e5 dxe5 21. Bxa8 Rxa8 22. Qb3 Nc4 23. h4 Bh6 24. Rad1 $16 {[%cal Gc3e4]}) 18. e5 $1 dxe5 19. h4 $1 gxh4 (19... g4 20. Nd2 Rad8 21. Qa4 Nxd2 22. Qxa6 $18) 20. Nxh4 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Re5,Re6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Gg2h3]}) 12... Nh5 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bd2 Nc4 15. b3 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Nf6 17. Rac1 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4,Yf6d7,Yh2h4,Yg2h3] We have a small but long-lasting advantage. The queenside is well defended, and it won’t be easy for Black to find good counterplay.}) (9... Bxa6 {Now we have transposed into the Benko, where I believe White has good chances with the Fianchetto variation.} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Rb1 $5 Qa5 {is the most logical move, preparing ...Rfb8 and ...Ng4.} (11... Nb6 $6 12. b3 {[%csl Ya6,Yb6]} Bb7 {[%csl Rd5]} 13. e4 Ba6 14. Re1 Ng4 15. Bb2 Nd7 16. Na4 $16) (11... Ng4 {[%cal Gg4e5,Gd8a5]} 12. Bd2 $1 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. b3 $1 {[%csl Gc4] An important move. We need control over the c4 square.} Qa5 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Ga5a3]} 15. Qc2 Qa3 {A typical idea where Black wants to close the queenside, simply preventing White from playing a4. Now it’s clear that Black’s next two moves will be ...Rfc8, followed by ...c4.} 16. Bc1 Qb4 $1 (16... Qa5 $6 17. a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3] Here we go! Just like in the main line, where Black plays 11...Qa5, we go for a4 again! It's crucial for us to remember this structure.} Nf3+ 18. Bxf3 Qxc3 19. Qa2 $1 {Of course, we don’t want to trade queens and make Black’s life easier. With Bd2, we will push the queen from c3 and continue to slowly build up our position.} Rfb8 (19... Qa5 $6 20. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Re7]} Ra7 21. Rfc1 Rb8 22. Bd2 Qd8 23. b4 $18 {1-0 Wang,Y (2732)-Bologan,V (2690) Olympiad-39 Khanty-Mansiysk 2010 (3.1)}) 20. Bd2 Qe5 21. Qc2 h5 22. h3 $16 {[%cal Gg1g2,Yh5h4,Yg3g4,Gf1d1,Gd2f4]}) 17. a3 $1 Nf3+ 18. Bxf3 Qxc3 19. Qa2 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1d2] A novelty, but actually the same idea as we saw in the 16...Qa5 line. We definitely don’t want to trade queens.} Rfb8 20. Bd2 Qf6 {A tricky move by Black. If we're not careful, we could miss the dangerous ...Bd3 idea!} (20... Qe5 21. b4 $1 $16) 21. Qc2 {[%cal Ra6d3,Gb3b4]} (21. b4 Bd3 $3 $11 {[%csl Ra2][%cal Ga8a2,Gb8b1]}) 21... h5 22. b4 cxb4 23. Rxb4 $14) (11... Qc7 $6 {[%cal Gf8b8] Generally, I think that in this position, with the bishop on a6, the queen doesn’t belong on c7, only on a5.} 12. b3 Rfb8 13. Qc2 Nb6 {[%csl Rd5]} 14. Rd1 Bc8 (14... Nfd7 15. Bd2 Ne5 16. Ne1 $1 $146 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ge2e4,Gf2f4] . Nice move. We avoid the exchange, as the knight on e5 no longer serves a significant purpose. We will prepare h3-e4-f4, kicking the knight from e5 and taking control of the center. With the knight on e1, the d3 square is covered.}) (14... Bb7 15. e4 $18 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7,Gd5,Ge4]}) 15. h3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Bf5 16. e4 Bc8 17. a4 {[%csl Ga4,Gb3]} Ba6 18. Bb2 $18 {1-0 Korobov,A (2671)-Cerrajeria Ruiz,J (2064) ESP-chT Rapid Toledo 2022 (9)}) 12. Bd2 Rfb8 {Here, I would offer the rare but logical} 13. a4 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2b3] simply preparing b3, from where Black will have difficulty breaking the queenside structure.} ({Immediately} 13. b3 $6 {is not good because of the strong} Ne8 $1 {[%csl Rc3]} 14. Qc2 Qa3 {[%csl Ga3]} 15. Rfc1 Nc7 $132 {[%cal Gc7b5]}) 13... Qc7 (13... Ng4 14. Qc2 $1 Nge5 15. Nxe5 Nxe5 16. b3 Rb7 17. h3 Rab8 18. Rfc1 Qb6 19. Be1 $16 {[%cal Gg1h2]}) 14. b3 $1 Nb6 15. Ng5 $5 {[%cal Gg5e4]} h6 16. Nge4 Nxe4 (16... Nh7 17. f4 $1 $146 Bd4+ 18. Kh1 Qd8 19. g4 $36 {[%csl Ya6,Ya8,Yb6,Yb8][%cal Ge4g3,Ge2e4]}) 17. Bxe4 Rb7 18. Qc2 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Ge4g6] Aiming for Bxg6.} Qc8 (18... Rab8 $2 19. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 20. Qxg6 $16 {[%cal Gd2h6]}) 19. Rfc1 Nd7 20. Bg2 Rab8 21. Bh3 $14 {The result of our a4-b3 strategy is clear. We have a very pleasant position. All of Black's pieces are concentrated on the queenside, where I don’t see any threats or counterplay. From here, we will slowly improve our position. We can start with Be1 and Ne4. There are always ideas like Bf1 followed by h3-g4, or sometimes simply Na2 followed by b4—it all depends on Black's response. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.40.}) (9... Bf5 10. O-O Ne4 $6 (10... Nxa6 11. a3 $1 {[%cal Ra6b4] would transpose to the main line.}) 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf3g5] Such a strong positional move! We threat 13.Ng5, and Black is forced to give up the light-squared bishop for the knight on f3.} Bxf3 13. exf3 Nxa6 14. Re1 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gh3f1,Gf1c4,Yh2h4,Yh4h5]}) 10. O-O Bf5 {Seems as the most logical move. 11...Nb4 can be a threat, as well as ideas involving ...Ne4.} 11. a3 {[%cal Ra6b4]} (11. a4 Nb4 12. Ne1 Qc8 $13) 11... Qc7 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gc5c4]} 12. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4] With this move, we prevent any future ...Ng4 ideas, while also preparing to push g4 and move the bishop off the f5-b1 diagonal.} (12. Nd2 {looks like an interesting alternative for White. It prevents ...Ne4 and prepares e4.} Nb4 13. e4 Bg4 (13... Bc8 $2 14. e5 $1 {[%csl Gg2]} Ne8 15. Nc4 Ba6 16. b3 $1 Bxc4 17. bxc4 Bxe5 18. Bb2 Na6 19. Nb5 Qd7 20. Bxe5 dxe5 21. d6 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Re8,Rf8][%cal Ga8c8,Gg2h3]}) 14. Bf3 $1 Bh3 $1 (14... Bxf3 $6 {would actually be a mistake here. After} 15. Nxf3 c4 {we have the strong} 16. Bh6 $1 {either trading the dark-square bishops or creating a passed pawn after axb4.} Bxh6 (16... Nd3 $6 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4,Yd3,Yd4][%cal Gd1d2]}) 17. axb4 Qb6 18. Ra4 Bg7 19. b5 Nd7 20. Rxc4 Bxc3 21. Rxc3 Qxb5 22. b3 $14 {[%cal Gc3c7,Gf3d4] /. Nd4-Nc6 is coming, and we also have a dangerous passed b pawn. It’s going to be a tough task for Black to defend.}) 15. Nc4 $5 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 Na6 17. Bg5 {[%cal Ge4e5]} h6 $1 (17... Rfb8 18. e5 Ne8 19. e6 $1 f5 20. h4 $16 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 18. Bd2 Qb7 19. Rb1 Nc7 20. a4 $13 {[%cal Rc7b5]}) 12... Rfb8 (12... Ne4 {looks like the most logical move, but it is refuted by the strong} 13. Na2 $1 {We avoid the exchange and threat 14.Nh4!, hitting the bishop on f5 and forcing Black to deal with the pressure.} c4 14. Nh4 (14. Nd4 Qb6 $1 15. Nxf5 gxf5 {[%cal Ge4g3]} 16. Bxe4 fxe4 17. Qc2 {[%csl Rc4,Re4]} e3 $1 $132) 14... Rfc8 15. g4 {[%csl Re4,Rf5]} c3 $1 16. Nxf5 gxf5 17. bxc3 Qc4 $1 (17... Nxc3 18. Nxc3 Qxc3 19. Rb1 fxg4 20. hxg4 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gg2f3,Gd1b3] We have the bishop pair and a passed pawn. Black is weak on the light squares, and we definitely have a safer endgame.}) 18. Qc2 (18. gxf5 Nb4 $3 19. Bxe4 Nxa2 20. Bd3 Nxc3 21. Bxc4 Nxd1 22. Rb1 Nxf2 23. Bb5 Ne4 24. Bc6 Ra5 $11) 18... Nxc3 19. Nxc3 Qxc3 20. Qxc3 Bxc3 21. Rb1 fxg4 22. hxg4 Nc5 23. Bf3 $13 {The bishop pair and a passed pawn give us slightly better chances in the endgame.}) 13. g4 $1 Bd7 14. e4 h5 $5 (14... c4 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5b3,Gc5d3]} 15. Qe2 (15. Nd4 Nc5 16. Nc6 Bxc6 17. dxc6 Qxc6 18. e5 Nfe4 $132) 15... Nb4 {[%cal Ra8a1]} (15... Nc5 $6 16. e5 $1 $36) 16. e5 $5 {I prefer this move because it leads to a highly dangerous position where Black struggles to find a good defense.} Nfxd5 17. Ng5 e6 18. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Nxd5 {Critical moment for Black. He should continue with the strong} Qd8 $1 21. Qf3+ Kg8 22. Nf6+ Bxf6 23. exf6 {[%cal Yg8f7,Yf3f4]} Be8 24. Bd2 Rxf1+ 25. Bxf1 $44 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gf1c4] We enter a very interesting endgame with a strong f6 pawn and control over the dark squares. According to the engine, the evaluation is 0.00, but I believe we have good practical chances to win this endgame.}) 15. g5 Ne8 (15... Nh7 16. e5 $1 $16) 16. Nh4 {[%cal Gf2f4] Now it's quite obvious that we are preparing an attack on the kingside with f4–f5. It sounds crazy, but we need just one more move to have a winning position. Therefore, Black must react very quickly.} Qa5 $1 {[%cal Gg7c3]} (16... c4 17. Kh1 $18 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]}) {Critical position for us. I’ve analyzed a few options for White, but} 17. f4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] seems the most interesting, as it leads to a complex and unclear positions.} (17. a4 {[%cal Ga1a3]} Bxc3 $1 18. bxc3 Qxc3 19. Ra3 Qd4 20. Qxd4 cxd4 21. Nf3 Rb4 22. Bd2 Rb2 $11) (17. Qd2 $5 Nac7 18. f4 Nb5 19. f5 gxf5 20. Qf2 Nxc3 $1 21. bxc3 Qxc3 22. Nxf5 Bxf5 23. Qxf5 Qxa1 24. Qxf7+ Kh7 $11) 17... Bxc3 18. f5 $5 {Interesting piece sacrifice. I'll provide some deep analysis, but in my opinion, without looking at the engine, it seems almost impossible to defend this position.} Bd4+ (18... gxf5 $6 19. Qxh5 $1 Ng7 20. Qh6 Rxb2 $3 {The only move to save the game!} 21. Bxb2 Bxb2 22. Rad1 $1 {[%cal Rb2d4]} (22. Rab1 Qd2 23. Rxb2 Qxb2 24. Nf3 {[%cal Gg5g6]} Nh5 $3 $11 {[%cal Gb2g7,Gg7h8]}) (22. Nf3 $5 Bd4+ $1 23. Nxd4 cxd4 24. Rf4 {[%cal Gf4h4]} Qc3 25. Raf1 d3 $3 26. Rh4 Ne8 {[%csl Gc3,Gh8][%cal Gc3h8]} 27. Qh7+ Kf8 28. exf5 Qg7 29. g6 Nac7 $11) 22... Qxa3 $1 (22... Bd4+ $2 23. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 24. exf5 $18 {[%cal Gh4g6]}) (22... Qc3 23. g6 $1 fxg6 24. Nxg6 {[%cal Gh6h8,Gh8a8]} Kf7 25. exf5 $18 {[%cal Gd1e1]}) 23. g6 fxg6 24. Nxg6 $13 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gg6e7] The idea is to play e5, followed by d6 or Nxe7, to keep opening the position and expose Black's king.}) 19. Kh1 Ng7 $1 20. fxg6 fxg6 21. Nxg6 Qd8 $1 22. Rb1 Bb5 $1 {One more important defensive move! In short, after Black plays ...e5 at some point, he will have the strong defensive resource ...Qc8–Rb7, defending along the 7th rank. It's a very deep idea.} (22... Nc7 $6 {[%cal Gc7b5] Seems like a human move, but it's already a mistake. After} 23. b4 $1 Nb5 24. Rb3 cxb4 (24... Qe8 25. Nh4 $18 {[%cal Gb3f3,Gg5g6]}) 25. Rxb4 Bc3 26. Rc4 $14 {/ we claim a solid advantage.}) 23. Rf3 e5 $3 (23... Nc7 $6 24. b4 $1 e6 25. bxc5 Bxc5 {Here, we have three solid options. If I were playing this position, I would definitely go for} 26. Rf8+ {because after} (26. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4]} Qd7 $1 27. Nh4 Rf8 28. g6 Rxf3 29. Nxf3 Rf8 $1 30. Qh6 Nge8 31. Qxh5 Nf6 32. Qh4 $13 {[%cal Gc1h6]}) (26. Rf6 Bf1 $3 27. Rxb8 Bxg2+ 28. Kxg2 Rxb8 29. Qd3 $13 {[%cal Gc1d2]}) 26... Qxf8 27. Nxf8 Rxf8 28. e5 $13 {[%cal Ge5d6,Gc1b2] everything is hanging on the board, and it visually looks winning for White.}) 24. Rf6 $13 {I think we can leave the position here. We threat 24.a4 and 25.Rxd6. The position is still dangerous for Black, and they need to continue making precise moves to maintain equality. From my perspective, after 18.f5!?, the position becomes much easier to play for White, and it’s Black who now needs to play like the engine to survive!} (24. Nh8 $5 Kxh8 25. g6 Kg8 26. Rf7 Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gb8b7] Here we can see why 22...Bb5 was an important defensive move for Black. Without that move, Black wouldn't have this strong defensive resource.} 27. a4 Bc4 28. Qd2 Rb7 29. Qh6 Rxf7 30. Qh7+ Kf8 31. Bh6 Qd7 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Bg5+ Rf6 34. Qxg7+ Kd8 35. Qxf6+ Kc7 {[%csl Gc7]} 36. Bh6 Nb4 $11) *

