{[%evp 0,27,19,38,15,11,35,37,43,12,20,20,19,7,37,24,42,7,54,50,68,68,62,60,68,86,54,96,53,92]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 c5 5. d5 $5 d6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {I believe this is the precise move order. We don't develop the knight to c3 until we see how Black reacts.} Na6 {Black's most common continuation. The idea is to play ...Nc7 to support ...b5 on the queenside.} (7... e6 {Black is ready to transpose to the Benoni after 8. Nc3. The only problem for him is that we have a strong alternative with} 8. dxe6 $1 Bxe6 (8... fxe6 $6 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Bg5 $1 {A very strong idea. We simply want to take on f6, create a battery on the d-file, jump with the knight to e4, and win the d6 pawn.} h6 (10... d5 11. a3 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga1c1,Yb2b4]} (11. cxd5 exd5 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Qxd5+ Qxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxb2 15. Rab1 Bg7 {1-0 Cori Tello,D (2413)-Duzhakov,I (2421) El Aguila Masters Utebo 2017 (3)} 16. Ng5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd5c7]}) 11... Rb8 (11... dxc4 12. Qa4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Re6][%cal Ga4c4]}) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Rc1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Gb2b4]}) 11. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 12. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Gd3g6]} Kg7 13. Rad1 {[%csl Rd6]} Be7 (13... Nd4 $5 14. Nd2 $1 Qb6 15. b3 (15. Nde4 $18 {[%cal Ge2e3] was the better way to gain a decisive advantage.}) 15... Bd7 16. Nde4 Be7 17. e3 Nf5 18. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2f4]} g5 {1-0 Gabrielian,A (2506)-Popov,M (2378) Voronezh op-A 21st 2017 (8)} 19. f4 $1 g4 20. h3 h5 21. hxg4 hxg4 22. Nf2 $18 {[%csl Rg4]}) 14. Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rd6]}) 9. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rb7]} Bc8 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gg5e4] A critical moment for Black. He should go for the strong novelty} Re8 $1 $146 {We will examine three different ways Black defended the d6-pawn, and none of them is good for him.} (11... Ne5 $6 {½-½ Ghaem Maghami,E (2531)-Issa,R (2386) Asia zt 3.1 Amman 2019 (5)} 12. Nge4 $1 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxc4 14. b3 $1 d5 $1 (14... Ne5 15. Qxd6 Qxd6 16. Nxd6 $18 {[%csl Gd6,Gf4,Gg2][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1d1] Black's position is completely lost.}) (14... Bxa1 $4 15. Qxa1 Ne5 16. Rd1 $18 {[%cal Gd1d6]}) 15. Nxc5 g5 $5 16. bxc4 gxf4 17. cxd5 Bxa1 18. Qxa1 fxg3 19. hxg3 b6 20. Nd3 $16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Ga1d4,Gg1g2,Gf1h1,Gd3e5,Ge2e4,Gg2f3] We have more than decent compensation. The next moves will be Qd4-e4, then Bf3, Kg2, and Rh1. The center is strong, and Black's king is very weak. According to the engine, the evaluation is +1.15.}) (11... Nd4 $2 {1-0 Malaniuk,V (2572)-Tseshkovsky,V (2558) Krasnodar 2000 (9) really doesn't make sense since we will not only kick that knight all the way back to h6, but the d6-pawn will fall anyway.} 12. e3 $1 Nf5 13. Nge4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Be6 15. g4 $1 Nh6 (15... Ne7 16. Bxd6 $18 {[%cal Ge4c5]}) 16. h3 $1 {[%csl Rh6]} Bxc4 17. Re1 f5 18. Nxd6 $18 {[%cal Gd6c4,Gd6b7,Gg2d5]}) ({Passive moves like} 11... Ne8 $6 {are rarely a good option.} 12. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf1d1,Gg5e4]} h6 13. Nge4 g5 14. Bxd6 Nxd6 {½-½ Kryakvin,D (2594)-Piorun,K (2601) Molodezhka-POL online Lichess.org INT blitz 2020} 15. Qxd6 $1 Qxd6 16. Nxd6 $18 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gg2d5,Gc3e4]}) 12. Nge4 $1 (12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. Bxd6 h6 14. Nge4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bh3 16. Bxh3 Rxe4 17. Bxc5 Rxe2 $132) 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 {[%csl Rd6]} Bh3 $1 (13... Bxb2 $6 14. Nxd6 $5 Bxa1 15. Nxe8 Qxe8 16. Qxa1 Nd4 17. Kh1 $1 $16 {[%csl Gf4,Yf6,Gg2,Yg7,Yh6][%cal Ge2e3]}) 14. Bxh3 Rxe4 15. Rc1 $1 Rd4 16. Qe1 d5 17. cxd5 Qxd5 18. b3 $14 {[%csl Gf4,Gh3][%cal Gh3g2,Gg2f3,Ge2e3] The bishop pair will be our nuclear weapon in such an open position. With the board wide open, the bishops have the freedom to control key squares and create threats across the board. According to the engine, we have a pleasant +0.40 advantage.}) (7... b5 8. cxb5 a6 9. bxa6 Nxa6 10. Nc3 {is analyzed in the previous chapter.}) (7... Re8 {An interesting preparatory move here. We continue with the important} 8. Re1 $1 {still not developing the knight to c3. We don't go for the classical Benoni; instead, we focus on Nfd2 ideas, keeping the knight on b1 ready to jump to d2 instead of c3.} a6 (8... e6 $6 9. dxe6 Rxe6 10. Nc3 h6 11. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gd1c2,Ga1d1]}) 9. a4 e6 10. Nfd2 $1 {Here, we can see one of the benefits of not playing Nc3 too early. We always keep the extra option of developing the b1 knight to d2.} exd5 11. cxd5 Nbd7 12. Nc4 Nb6 13. Nxb6 (13. Nca3 $5 Bd7 14. Nc3 Nc8 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8]} 15. Nc4 Rb8 16. a5 Ng4 $1 $132) 13... Qxb6 14. a5 Qd8 15. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3]} Bd7 (15... Ne4 $6 {looks very tempting, but it's a strategic mistake. After we trade dark-squared bishops, our knight will dominate Black's light-squared bishop, while the pawn on a5 plays a crucial role in blocking the entire queenside.} 16. Bxe4 $1 Rxe4 17. Bc3 $1 {[%csl Gb1,Yc8][%cal Gb1d2]}) 16. e4 Bb5 (16... b5 17. axb6 Qxb6 18. Bc3 $14 {[%csl Ya6][%cal Gb1d2]}) 17. Bc3 $14 {[%cal Gb1a3,Gb1d2,Yh2h4,Yg2h3] Na3–Nc4 is always an idea, but Nd2 is also a strong option, especially when Black plays ...Nd7, allowing us to push h4-h5 and, with Nf3, support the kingside attack.}) (7... a6 8. a4 e6 9. Re1 Re8 10. Nfd2 {would transpose to 7...Re8.}) 8. Nc3 Nc7 9. e4 Rb8 (9... a6 10. a4 Rb8 {would transpose to 9...Rb8.}) (9... Bg4 10. a4 $1 Qd7 {½-½ Marin,M (2548)-Iturrizaga Bonelli,E (2603) ESP-chT CECLUB Titulo sf2 Div 1 Sabadell 2011 (1.1)} 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bd2 Bh3 14. Re1 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 e6 16. h3 $16 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gd2f4]}) (9... e6 10. h3 {After 10...exd5 11.cxd5, we are ready to prevent 11...Bg4.} exd5 11. cxd5 Nd7 12. a4 b6 13. h4 $5 $146 {[%cal Yh4h5] Besides controlling g5 square, it's always good to provoke the kingside with h5 ideas.} (13. Bf4 $16 {[%csl Rd6]}) 13... h6 14. Re1 Ne8 15. Be3 $16 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1d1] Rad1–Qd2 is coming. We have good development, while Black's pieces are somewhat stuck, and he hasn't achieved ...b5 on the queenside. That's enough for us to have a dominant position.}) 10. a4 $1 b6 {[%cal Ga7a6]} (10... a6 {without ...b6 always allows us to play} 11. a5 $1 {where after} b5 12. axb6 {[%csl Ra6,Gc6] a6 remains weak, and we also get the c6 outpost for our knight.} Rxb6 13. Nd2 $1 $16 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd2b3,Gb3a5,Ga5c6]}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] Important move. We are preparing e5!} e5 (11... a6 $2 12. e5 $1 {After we manage to play e5, Black's position strategically collapses.} Nfe8 (12... Ng4 $6 13. Bf4 $1 dxe5 (13... b5 $2 14. exd6 $1 exd6 15. Ne4 $1 $146 bxc4 16. Bxd6 Re8 17. Bxc5 Bxb2 18. Rb1 c3 19. h3 Bf5 20. Nd4 $18 {[%cal Gd4c6]}) 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 $16 {[%csl Yb8,Yc7,Yc8,Re7][%cal Gd1e2]}) 13. h3 $1 {[%cal Rc8g4]} b5 14. b3 $1 $18 {[%cal Ga1a2,Yb5b4,Yc3e4]}) (11... Nd7 {[%cal Re4e5]} 12. Qd3 a6 13. Rb1 {[%cal Gc1f4,Yb2b4]} Ne5 (13... b5 $6 {could be interesting as an attempt to open the queenside, but unfortunately for Black, it doesn't work.} 14. axb5 axb5 15. Nxb5 $1 Nxb5 16. cxb5 Qa5 17. Bf1 $16 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc1d2]}) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bh6 Bg7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gh2h4] Perfect moment for this move! 17.h4 could be an interesting alternative.}) 12. dxe6 Nxe6 (12... Bxe6 $2 13. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Rd6]} Nfe8 14. e5 $1 $146 {A strong improvement over the previous game. We almost win by force.} d5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Ra3 {[%cal Ga3d3]} c4 18. e6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Ge6e7,Gf3g5]}) 13. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rd6]} Rb7 14. Ra3 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga3d3] Rd3 is coming. Black has no resources to defend the d6 pawn.} *

