{[%evp 0,33,10,27,11,13,31,25,37,17,50,43,35,46,42,50,48,-1,52,52,26,35,51,49,55,54,54,55,52,45,52,56,47,54,54,86]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O O-O 7. d5 $1 Na6 (7... Ne4 8. Qc2 $1 f5 9. Ng5 $1 {The e4 square is strategically important for both sides, so it's time to eliminate the knight!} Nd6 (9... Nc5 10. Nc3 a5 11. e4 $1 e5 12. exf5 gxf5 13. f4 $1 h6 14. Nf3 e4 15. Nh4 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Yf5][%cal Gg2h3,Gc1e3] Bh3 will definitely be a strong idea for us and a big threat to Black. The bad bishop on b7 is far from helping the kingside.}) (9... Nxg5 10. Bxg5 {[%cal Gg5e7]} d6 (10... h6 $2 {Delchev,A (2503)-Hamitevici,V (2456) Chalons en Champagne FRA 2021 was a terrible blunder, which Delchev unfortunately failed to punish.} 11. Bxe7 $1 Qxe7 12. d6 {After this move, White simply wins the game.} Qf6 (12... Qxd6 13. Bxb7 Nc6 14. Bxa8 Rxa8 15. Nc3 $18 {[%cal Ga1d1]}) 13. Bxb7 Qxb2 14. Qxb2 Bxb2 15. Bxa8 c6 (15... Bxa1 16. dxc7 Na6 17. c8=Q $3 {This was the key idea behind the entire line. An amazing move!!} Rxc8 18. Bb7 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rc8]}) 16. Nd2 Bxa1 17. Rxa1 Na6 18. Bxc6 dxc6 19. Nf3 $18 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ga1d1]}) 11. e4 $1 Nd7 12. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Ge6] The bishop on b7 is bad and misplaced, while the e6 square definitely looks like a future outpost for our pieces!}) 10. Nc3 Na6 11. e4 h6 12. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3f4]} (12. Nf3 {is also possible, but I prefer 12.Nh3 since we can later play Nf4.} e6 $1 $14) 12... Qe8 (12... e5 13. b3 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Bxe4 d6 16. f3 $14 {[%csl Ya6,Rb7,Yg6,Rg7,Yh6][%cal Gh3f2,Gc1e3] /}) (12... e6 13. exf5 Nxf5 (13... exf5 14. Nf4 Qe8 (14... Qf6 15. Be3 Nxc4 16. Ne4 fxe4 17. Qxc4 Nc5 18. b4 Ba6 19. b5 Bb7 20. Rad1 $16) 15. b3 g5 16. Nd3 f4 {At first, it looks like a promising attack, but all three minor pieces are far away from our king. With a few precise moves, we will refute the attack and maintain a stable advantage.} 17. Re1 Qg6 18. Ba3 Nc5 19. Rad1 Bd4 20. gxf4 Rxf4 21. Re2 $16 {[%csl Yc5,Yd4,Yf4][%cal Gc3b5]}) 14. Bd2 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Yg6,Yh6][%cal Gh3f4] /}) 13. Re1 e5 14. b3 Nc5 15. exf5 Nxf5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gf5d4]} (15... gxf5 16. Bb2 a5 17. Nd1 $16 {[%cal Gd1e3,Ga2a3,Gb3b4] Ne3 will support the kingside, while a3-b4 will not only force the knight off c5 but also threat to continue with c5.}) 16. b4 {[%csl Rc5]} Na6 17. a3 Qf7 18. Ne4 Nd4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} 19. Qd3 Nf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qxf3 21. Re3 Qf5 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7] In this position, Stockfish prefers a more strategic line with 22.Kg2-f3, slowly building up the position. Since Black's two minor pieces are far away from the king, I would suggest the interesting} 22. g4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5]} (22. Kg2 d6 23. f3 $14 {[%cal Gh3f2] Stockfish 14 (3639)- LCZero (3623) tcec-chess.com INT 2021}) 22... Qxg4+ (22... Qf7 23. g5 $1 h5 24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. gxf6 Qxf6 26. Rg3 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Rg6]}) 23. Rg3 Qh5 (23... Qf5 24. f3 $18 {[%cal Ga1a2,Ga2g2]}) 24. f3 Rf7 25. Kg2 Raf8 26. Nhf2 d6 27. Rh3 Qf5 28. Bxh6 Bxh6 29. Rxh6 Qxf3+ 30. Qxf3 Rxf3 31. Rxg6+ Kf7 32. Re6 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7] /+-. According to the engine, White is slightly better, but only if Black makes the most precise defensive moves!}) (7... e6 8. Nc3 exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. Nd4 {[%cal Gc1f4] Centralizing the knight is always a good idea in this type of structure.} Na6 {[%csl Gd4]} 11. Bf4 Nc5 (11... Nh5 12. Be3) 12. Ndb5 d6 13. b4 $1 Ncd7 14. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Yb6,Rb7,Yc7,Gd5,Yd6] Sonis,F (2483)-Vocaturo,D (2617) Premium Chess Arena INT 2020 The bad bishop on b7, Black's weak pawn structure, our strong knight, and the vulnerable queenside light squares assure us of a dominant position.}) (7... b5 $5 {Interesting move. Black is trying to undermine White's center.} 8. Qb3 Qc8 9. Qxb5 c6 10. dxc6 Bxc6 (10... Nxc6 $6 11. Nc3 Rb8 12. Qa4 Ba8 (12... Ba6 $2 {Cheparinov,I (2672)-Salgado Lopez,I (2624) Camarinas 2013 was an interesting try by Salgado. Unfortunately for Cheparinov, he missed the win here.} 13. b3 $1 (13. c5 $16) 13... Ne4 {[%cal Rg7a1]} 14. Nxe4 Bxa1 15. Bf4 {[%csl Ra1,Ra6]} Rb4 16. Qa3 {[%csl Ra1]} Bg7 17. Ne5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rc6]}) 13. a3 d6 14. Rb1 Nd7 {Todorov,O (2317)-Fernandez Aguado,J (2309) France 2006} 15. Qc2 {We keep the pawn, and Black has no counterplay.} Nd8 16. Nd2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qb7+ 18. Kg1 Ne6 19. b3 $14 {[%cal Ga3a4,Gh2h4] /}) 11. Qb3 (11. Qg5 $146 h6 12. Qe3 d5 13. Ne5 $14 {also seems fine for White}) 11... a5 $5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Daneshvar,B (2540)-Poormosavi,S (2413) Tehran IRI 2023} (11... d6 12. Nc3 Nbd7 13. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gf1c1,Ge3d4,Ye3g5,Yf6g4]}) 12. Be3 ({Another move for an advantage is} 12. a4 Ne4 13. Na3 Nc5 14. Qe3 Nxa4 15. Qxe7 $14 {[%csl Ya8,Yb8,Yc8]}) 12... a4 13. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Gb1d2] Black definitely has some active play, but it's going to be hard to prove it.}) 8. Nc3 Nc5 {So far, we've followed the main line. Here, I propose} 9. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] with the idea of pushing e4.} (9. Nd4 $6 {is the most played move by White, but after} e5 $1 10. Nb3 (10. Nc2 a5 $11) 10... d6 {[%cal Ga7b5] Black seems solid.}) 9... Nfe4 (9... e6 10. e4 d6 11. Qc2 $1 (11. Bg5 h6 12. Bd2 $1 a5 13. Qc2 Re8 14. Rad1 exd5 {0-1 Vlasak,L (2461)-Hagner,B (2311) Bundesliga 2425 Germany 2024 (3.7)} (14... Qd7 15. Bh3 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Qd8 16. Be3 exd5 17. exd5 {[%csl Rb7]} h5 $5 {[%cal Rf6g4]} 18. b3 Ng4 19. Bd4 $14 {0.60}) 15. exd5 $1 $14 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gf3d4]}) 11... a5 12. h3 $146 e5 (12... exd5 13. exd5 Ba6 14. Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c6] Beautiful move! We create multiple threats, making the c4 pawn unimportant.} Bxc4 15. Nc6 Qd7 (15... Re8 16. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rd8]} Qd7 17. Qxc4 Nfxe4 18. Rxe4 $1 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Qxh3 20. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Gc6,Gd2,Ge4]}) 16. Re7 Qc8 17. Be3 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8,Rf8][%cal Ge3d4] For one pawn, we have gained a lot of activity. Black looks completely paralyzed.}) 13. Be3 Nfd7 14. b3 f5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. Rad1 e4 17. Nd4 Ne5 18. Nce2 $14 {[%cal Ge2f4]}) 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qc2 {The most logical move - we want to remove the knight and push e4} f5 {[%csl Ge4]} 12. Ng5 $1 Nxg5 (12... Nc5 13. e4 $1 h6 14. exf5 $1 {A powerful piece sacrifice!} hxg5 15. Bxg5 Rxf5 16. Bxe7 Qc8 17. Re3 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rb7,Rc8][%cal Ga1e1]}) 13. Bxg5 h6 14. Bd2 e5 {Medvegy,Z (2524)-Maurizzi,M (2433) Europe-Echecs INT 2020} 15. e4 $1 {Seems like a reasonable improvement over previous games.} d6 (15... f4 {is not a threat since after} 16. gxf4 exf4 {we have} 17. e5 Qg5 18. e6 $18 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Rf4f3]}) 16. b4 $1 Qf6 17. a4 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga4a5,Ga1a3,Ge4f5] Our idea is to continue with a5, and also to capture on f5 at the right moment, supported by Ra3 to help defend the king along the third rank. 17...f4 is not a threat, since after 18.a5, we simply threat to capture on f4 and push e5. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.45.} *

