{[%evp 0,27,16,15,30,14,39,40,34,10,5,8,44,16,0,3,24,26,-19,27,25,21,13,15,-1,47,36,34,36,-23]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 Nc6 $5 {Black delays ...d6 to keep flexibility in the center, exert early pressure on d4, and potentially play ...d5 in one go if White allows it, rather than committing to a standard King's Indian structure, so we can react with} 6. d5 $5 {preventing all of that.} (6. Nc3 {would allow} d5) (6. O-O {is of course possible, but after} d6 {we lose the option to play d5, as analyzed in Chapter 6.}) 6... Na5 7. Na3 c5 (7... b5 $5 $146 {An interesting novelty that leads to unclear, complex positions.} 8. cxb5 a6 9. O-O axb5 10. Nxb5 Nxd5 $1 (10... Bb7 11. Nc3 c6 12. e4 cxd5 13. exd5 $14 {[%csl Ya5,Yb7][%cal Gf3d4] would allow us to keep the pawn without giving Black significant compensation.}) 11. Qxd5 c6 12. Qe4 d5 13. Qh4 cxb5 14. Bh6 {[%cal Gf3g5]} e6 15. Ng5 $13 {[%csl Ya5,Gg5,Gh4,Gh6][%cal Ge2e4] Black is already under significant pressure, and we have a promising position that requires precise defense to survive.}) 8. O-O (8. Nd2 d6 9. O-O Rb8 10. Rb1 a6 11. b3 b5 12. Bb2 Bd7 13. Re1 $13) 8... d6 9. Re1 e6 (9... Bf5 10. Ng5 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} a6 11. e4 Bg4 12. f3 Bd7 (12... h6 $6 {initially seems logical, aiming to drive the knight back to h3, but White has a strong alternative starting with} 13. e5 $1 dxe5 14. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 15. fxg4 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Re5,Yg6,Yh6][%cal Gg4g5];1-0 Malikentzos,S (2432)-Papadopoulos,G (2378) GRE-ch 69th Thessaloniki 2019 (8) leaving Black with a damaged structure full of potential targets for us. The threat of 16.g5, along with the potential Bh3-Be6, adds pressure.}) 13. f4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5]} (13. Rb1 b5 14. b3 Rb8 15. Bd2 bxc4 16. bxc4 Qc7 17. Qe2 $14) 13... e5 14. dxe6 {[%csl Rd6]} Bxe6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Rb1 Kh8 17. Bd2 Nc6 18. Nc2 {[%cal Gb2b4]} a5 19. a4 Nd7 20. Kh1 $14 {[%csl Yd6,Ye6][%cal Gc2a3,Ga3b5] We have a slightly better position due to Black's slightly damaged structure. He has some compensation from the d4 outpost, but I believe that after Na3-Nb5 followed by Bc3, it won't be as big a problem as the weakness on d6.}) 10. e4 {An important moment for Black. I believe the best continuation for Black is} Re8 $1 {fighting for control of the e-file.} (10... exd5 {seems like a reasonable move, but it would allow us to control the e-file and potentially trade the light-squared bishops via the h3 square. It will be a tough task for Black to bring the knight from a5 back into the game.} 11. exd5 Re8 (11... a6 12. Bf4 $146 Re8 13. Rxe8+ Nxe8 14. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1]}) 12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. Bd2 b6 14. Qf1 $14 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gb2b3,Gg2h3]}) 11. Bf4 {[%cal Ge4e5]} exd5 {is the most logical continuation for Black.} (11... Nh5 $6 {doesn't make much sense, as after} 12. Bg5 Bf6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 {Black exchanges dark-squared bishops but fails to stop the strong} (13... Qxf6 14. Nb5 $18 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d6]}) 14. e5 $1 dxe5 15. Nxe5 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5,Gg2]}) (11... a6 {also doesn't make much sense, as it allows} 12. e5 $1 {leading to complex positions where Black must find a series of accurate defensive moves.} dxe5 13. Nxe5 exd5 14. cxd5 Nh5 15. Qd2 Nxf4 16. gxf4 Bf8 17. d6 Bxd6 18. Rad1 Bc7 19. Nxg6 (19. Qc3 Qf6 20. Qxc5 Bb6 21. Qb4 Bc7) 19... Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Bd6 21. Ne5 Be6 22. Nc2 Nc6 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Rd3 $13 {[%cal Ge1c3,Gd3g3]}) 12. exd5 Rxe1+ 13. Qxe1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gf4d6]} b6 {[%csl Ga5]} (13... a6 14. Bxd6 $5 Qxd6 15. Qxa5 b6 16. Qd2 Ra7 17. Re1 Re7 18. Re2 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ga3c2,Gb2b3,Gc2e3]}) 14. Qe2 {[%cal Ga1e1] White has a slightly pleasant position due to control of the e-file, pressure on the d6 pawn, and the misplaced knight on a5. According to the engine, the evaluation is +0.20, indicating that Black's position is still holdable, but I favor our long-term chances.} *

