{[#]} {White to move} 18. h4 $1 {Not mentioned by Jones, but I believe this could be an interesting improvement over 18.Nce4 or 18.Rfe1. This move keeps the tension and waits for Black's plan. Most likely, Black will try} (18. Nec4 Na5 $1 {Black has no better option than to repeat moves here. He can't allow us to occupy the c4 square so easily, as this square is strategically important for our position.}) 18... Nd7 {aiming to exchange dark-squared bishops and take control over the dark squares.} 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Ne4 {This move is useful from several perspectives:  1. It centralizes the knight while also preventing any ...Rxe3 sacrifices.  2. Qb2 keeps the threat of controlling the a1-h8 diagonal.  3. 21.a3 is preparing to prevent ...a4 from Black, but also opens the a-file if it benefits us.  The most important idea in this position is that we need to play Rfc1! The rook belongs on c1 as it long-term prevents any future ...c4 ideas, which I allowed in the game against my student. The rook on e1 doesn't serve any special purpose, while on c1, it has many strategic roles.} *

